<h1>The Engineer</h1>
<p>On the morning of July 11, 1957, the engineer Paavo Nieminen woke up with a sentence in his mind, which ran: "I'm ill and I'm giving you a present: a bell." However, when he looked around, there was no one to be seen. Just him, his bed and the wall against which he breathed at night. So Paavo Nieminen, the engineer, got up (everything felt fine), put his shoes on, went to the toilet, had a wash, got dressed, chewed a slice of bread, walked to work, calculated the things he had been given to calculate, got numbers that varied only marginally, walked home, chewed two slices of bread, undressed, had a wash, went to the toilet, took his shoes off, and got into bed. The next morning he was awoken by a blue dog, rolling around on his carpet.</p>
<p>Now, the floor had wooden inlay. And on it was his bed. And here lay, Paavo Nieminen, the engineer. No trace of a dog. So he got up (why was it <em>blue</em>?), put his shoes on (no bite marks), went to the toilet, had a wash, got dressed, chewed a slice of bread, walked to work, calculated the things he had been given to calculate, got numbers that were sometimes different before the decimal point and sometimes after it, walked home, chewed two slices of bread, undressed, had a wash, went to the toilet, took his shoes off, and got into bed. The next morning, a Saturday, the bell rang.</p>
<p>Paavo Nieminen started out of his dream, heard the sound of the bell jingling through the corridor into his room, heard no barking – and got up. He got dressed quickly and reached the door, his heart bumping out of his collar, he pressed an eye to the peephole, read his name, pressed the other eye to it – and read his name again. So he opened the door. Mail. From Mom. A parcel. Inside, all kinds of preserves. Fish, minced meat, plums, beans When he pulled out the jar with the beans, they looked to him like eels that someone had placed in a barrel of water to soak, and which now, pressed closely together, stretched their heads out as though they were in danger of drowning. The bottom, full of mustard seeds is the excrement of the dead creatures, he thought.</p>
<p>The letter from his mother, squashed between four jars of minced meat, contained nothing new. Even at the age of thirty-six, bachelors were still in danger of starving, appropriate supplies of food were enclosed and feedback was requested.</p>
<p>Paavo Nieminen grabbed a handful of eels, stuffed them into his mouth, stared at the ground while chewing them from their tails upwards – and thought about the mailman, who was actually a parcelman. The parcel is the sum of my perceptions, just as I am the sum of the parcelman's perceptions, he thought, yet this time he did not immediately feel frightened – and afterwards there was enough time to pick the vodka out of the parcel. The eels in the glass stretched their heads as though they wanted to drink.</p>
<p>Eleven hours later Paavo Nieminen staggered into his bed and was asleep before his head hit the pillow.</p>
<p>Just before three o'clock he woke up from a dream that, by his first attempt to remember, he had already forgotten. Maybe, he said to himself while putting his shoes on and waddling into the bath, maybe the dream has forgotten me, too.</p>
<p>He brushed this thought away, shuffled into the kitchen, cooked himself two eggs, put them on the table and spooned them out alternately with two little jars of minced meat. Meanwhile, the newspaper in front of him was still talking about the <em>Great Finnish Triumph</em>. It had happened two days ago, on Thursday. On his way home from work he passed the Urheilupuisto Stadium and heard them roaring inside. Thousands of Finnish throats, propelling the runners around the cinder track. 1,500 metres – and in the end three Finns won. And they were all called Olavi. And had all covered the distance in 3 minutes 40 seconds. (And, of course, they were all born in '33).</p>
<p>The analysis of the photo-finish took a good ten minutes, corresponding to 4,500 metres or the distance run by three runners, and when the referees finally announced the winner, Paavo Nieminen was already walking over the walled Aurajoki towards Port Arthur, and learned only the next day – after taking the newspaper out of the mailbox on his way to work and reading it during his lunch break – that the three Olavis’ scores only differed in the figure after the decimal point. However, for two of them even that figure was identical and help was sought in their fathers’ names. (1) Olavi Salsola: 3'40.2". (2) Olavi Salonen: 3'40.2". (3) Olavi Vuorisalo: 3'40.3". Yet all three, it was reported, had broken the world record of the Hungarian Rózsavölgyi. It had not even lasted a year.</p>
<p>Anyway, today, he (Paavo Nieminen, the engineer) knew this, because he had heard it on the radio last night while he was basking in the vodka, today – on Sunday, haha – the newspaper would announce (it would have to!) that the <em>Great Finnish Triumph</em> was already out of date, because somewhere in Czechoslovakia people had roared a runner around the cinder track in an even shorter time. World record! On Friday evening. What a scream!</p>
<p>Paavo Nieminen tried to remember the runner's name, but the only thing that came to mind was "blue dog".</p>
<p>It had slipped away.<br/>He didn’t care.</p>
<p>The figure before the decimal point had been lower – and the one after probably too. And if not, it didn’t matter. He would be able to read it all after getting dressed and fetching the newspaper from the mailbox. The <em>Great Czechoslovakian Catastrophe </em>was just one and a half flights of stairs away. But for now he was sitting at the table, eating minced meat and drinking vodka out of eggshells.</p>
<p>When his eyes eventually dropped back to the newspaper, he read that Matti Nurmi was ninth in the <em>Great Finnish Triumph</em> on Thursday. Not at all bad, he thought, indeed remarkable. After all, Matti's father had built the house in Helsinki in which his own mother now lived. And he, Paavo Nieminen, the engineer, had gotten his first name from his father, who in turn had gotten it from Matti's father.</p>
<p>"That's what comes of Paavo Nurmi talking only to his legs," Paavo Nieminen said, poured an egg into his mouth and hit the table with his forehead.</p>
<p>When he woke up, the sun was lying behind the house, waiting to rise.</p>
<p>It will bleach all the wood, Paavo Nieminen thought, but what can I do?</p>
<p>"You could tell me what time it is," said the sun.</p>
<p>"3.27," said Paavo Nieminen, "time for bed.”</p>
<p>"Good night," said the sun.</p>
<p>"Goodbye," said Paavo Nieminen.</p>
<p>Ten minutes later he woke up in a lucid dream. Two blue dogs were sitting on his carpet and, just after he had opened his eyes, they started circling a clock in the shape of a box, which started moving with the blue dogs, counting down from 3.38.</p>
<p>Clack-clack-clack.</p>
<p>"You'll appreciate that we didn't bother with the tenths of seconds," said the blue dog, the leader. "A clock with a mechanism that clicks every second is bad enough. I mean, for one's hearing …"</p>
<p>Clack-clack.</p>
<p>"3.30 left," said the follower dog.</p>
<p>"So, what shall we talk about?" asked the dog leader, "Stará Boleslav? Port Arthur? Turku?"</p>
<p>"What's Stará Boleslav?"</p>
<p>"A town in Czechoslovakia, famous for being the place where Saint Wenceslaus was murdered. His brother Boleslav smashed him to pieces. A thousand years later the politically unstable Stanislav Jungwirth set a new world record in the 1500 metres there."</p>
<p>"3.20," said the dog.</p>
<p>"Stop," said Paavo Nieminen, "I need to check this 'unstable'-thing".</p>
<p>He stood up, put his shoes on and staggered downstairs into the blue-white checkered hallway, where the parcelman was about to stuff the Sunday newspaper into the mailbox. Paavo Nieminen ripped it out of his hands, ripped it out of the mailbox, ripped his eyes open, and he read on the front page: "Monday, July 15, 1957."</p>
<p>The time was 3.34. The sun in the back yard stretched out through the door the parcelman had left open, then took off. Paavo Nieminen was aware that he would have to walk to work in three hours, beneath the sun's welcoming laughter.</p>
<p>The parcelman strode through the blue-white gleaming hallway, and closed the door on his way out.</p>
<p>Paavo Nieminen climbed the stairs. He must have slept through a whole day altogether. And the blue dogs were gone, too.</p>
<p>Two and a half hours later he was still standing in his shoes in front of his bed. He went to the toilet, had a wash, got undressed and then dressed again, indifferently chewed some eels, dragged himself to work, polished a few decimal points, perspired, ground some numbers, got used to it, and went home, but not straight away. At 16 Linnankatu Street, passing the venerable old Kansallinen bookstore with indifference, his eyes glanced at a book, which was blue and white and otherwise quite unremarkable, except for its title, which was "The Sinequanonical Qualities of the Engineer."</p>
<p>He went into the shop, looked for the book, could not find it, heard that it was sold out, and asked for the copy from the shop window. He opened it, found formulae whose letters varied, saw numbers that changed here and there (or maybe not), and gazed at symbols, all of which he understood. When he left the shop, he saw the salesgirl putting the book back in the window. He went home, chewed some indifferent eels (these creatures were nocturnal), undressed (he had become pasty), had a wash (really pasty), went to the toilet, took his shoes off and went to bed. The next morning, he was dead.</p>
